{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568691"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:20:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:20:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21300"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21300"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.14,0.1,0.01,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14173"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104337"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14173"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21300"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86666"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"12908"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36264"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37080"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104337"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the cardiology outpatient clinic for assessment of possible ischaemic heart disease (IHD). He reports several months of central chest discomfort brought on by walking up hills and relieved by rest. He has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia and takes ramipril and atorvastatin. He does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well, with vital signs within normal limits. An exercise stress test is performed. Four minutes into the test, he developed ST depression in leads II, III and aVF.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Coronary angiography","Transthoracic echocardiography","Non-stress ECG","Coronary artery bypass grafting","Thrombolysis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronary angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial step in management for a person with exertional angina symptoms and intermediate to high pretest probability of ischaemic heart disease (IHD) who develops exercise-induced ST depression in the inferior leads. This finding is highly suggestive of inducible myocardial ischaemia. In this context, invasive coronary angiography is indicated to define coronary anatomy and guide further management, as the degree of stenosis identified on angiography is critical in determining whether revascularisation (such as percutaneous coronary intervention or coronary artery bypass grafting) is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransthoracic echocardiography\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for assessing cardiac structure and function, but it does not provide information about coronary anatomy or directly assess for coronary artery disease. It may be used adjunctively, but is not the initial step in this scenario where ischaemia has already been demonstrated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-stress ECG\u003C/strong\u003E (resting electrocardiogram) may be helpful for baseline assessment, but it is not sufficient to evaluate the significance of exercise-induced ischaemia in a high-risk individual. The stress test has already provided diagnostic information that necessitates further invasive assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronary artery bypass grafting\u003C/strong\u003E is a revascularisation procedure that may be indicated after coronary anatomy is defined, but it is not the initial step. The decision for surgery versus percutaneous intervention depends on angiographic findings and clinical context, which are obtained via coronary angiography.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombolysis\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for acute ST elevation myocardial infarction or other specific indications of acute coronary thrombosis. There is no evidence of acute infarction in this scenario, so thrombolysis is not appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the presence of exercise-induced ST depression in a person with an intermediate to high pretest probability of IHD warrants prompt invasive assessment to guide definitive management and reduce the risk of adverse cardiac events. Coronary angiography provides the anatomical detail necessary to rationalise and plan revascularisation if indicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Exercise-induced ST depression in the inferior leads during a stress test indicates myocardial ischaemia and warrants urgent invasive assessment.","Coronary angiography is the most appropriate initial step following a positive stress test in a person with angina symptoms and high risk factors.","The degree of coronary artery stenosis, determined by angiography, guides the need and rationalisation for revascularisation."],"references":["Timmis A, Raharja A, Archbold RA, Mathur A. Validity of inducible ischaemia as a surrogate for adverse outcomes in stable coronary artery disease. Heart. 2018;104(21):1733-1738. Available from: https://heart-bmj-com.acthealthlibrary.idm.oclc.org/content/104/21/1733.long","Neumann FJ, Sousa-Uva M, Ahlsson A, et al. 2018 ESC/EACTS Guidelines on myocardial revascularization [published correction appears in Eur Heart J. 2019 Oct 1;40(37):3096. doi: 10.1093/eurheartj/ehz507.]. Eur Heart J. 2019;40(2):87-165. Available from: https://www.escardio.org/Guidelines/Clinical-Practice-Guidelines/ESC-EACTS-Guidelines-in-Myocardial-Revascularisation-Guidelines-for","McLellan A, Prior D. Cardiac stress testing - stress electrocardiography and stress echocardiography. Aust Fam Physician. 2012 Mar;41(3):119-22. PMID: 22396924. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/march/cardiac-stress-testing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86666"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21300"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86666"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-01T07:55:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-01T07:56:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14173"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104337"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only 